{
  "answer": "In Allama Iqbal's \"Khitab ba Jawanan-e-Islam,\" the most heroic distillation of the ancestors' ideal—those desert Arabs who built empires—is this evocation of their boundless dominion: \"World-seizers and world-rulers, world-guardians and world-adorners.\"[^1]\n\nIn Cynewulf's *Andreas*, Andrew emerges as a present-tense hero of unyielding faith and miraculous command, nowhere more vividly than when he boldly orders a stone pillar to unleash a cataclysmic flood on his tormentors: \"Hear me now, marble-stone, by the Maker's decree...\"[^2]\n\nWhich is the harder ideal to live up to? Andrew's. Iqbal's forebears demand revival through action, pride, and worldly mastery—a high bar, but humanly attainable through will and motion. Andrew's demands divine fortitude: physical torture without breaking (\"unwavering courage\" amid gore and shattered bones[^3]), plus commanding the elements as God's thane. That's not just heroism; it's hagiographic.[^4]\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, \"Khitab ba Jawanan-e-Islam\" [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/13-khitab-ba-jawanan-e-islam/translation/#p-365462).\n\n[^2]: Cynewulf, *Andreas*, Chapter 1 [paragraph](/works/cynewulf-andreas-07b573/01/translation/#p-2e50c1).\n\n[^3]: Cynewulf, *Andreas*, Chapter 1 [paragraph](/works/cynewulf-andreas-07b573/01/translation/#p-34b202).\n\n[^4]: Cynewulf, *Andreas*, Chapter 1 [paragraph](/works/cynewulf-andreas-07b573/01/translation/#p-868413).",
